"{\n  \"text\": \"Hi everybody. I was inspired by Albert Howard's work about a hundred years ago, about 80 years ago, on sheet composting. And so I'm working with my friend Riley over at Messina Regenerative here at Messina Regenerative in Neadville, Texas, where we are trying to do composting at scale. You'll look behind me. I have about 15, about 12 barrels of organic waste, that's kitchen waste, uh, carrot tops, onion skins, that type of thing. And then over in the trailer, we got another nine that I'm bringing today. And all of this will make another gigantic pile similar to that one. That's probably about 10 cubic yards. Yeah, give or take. And that will get spread out into his garden space, and then we will make another one. You basically create this by adding the wood chips from over there, and we get those from all sorts of different people for free. They just come and drop it off because they have to pay to dump it, and we'll take them for free. And then we add the kitchen waste, and it's about two parts uh wood chips, one part kitchen waste, and then you add a bunch of water, mix it up as well as you can, and you let it sit. And it should heat up to about 130 degrees, and then the breakdown of that organic material will be very thorough. You'll find the wood chips become very small, and the food waste becomes gone, and it will heat up very nicely for about two months, and in that time you'll have to toss it or uh take the big tractor that we have back there, you can see it, and turn it over, give it a little bit more water if it's not raining enough. And you do this two or three times over a two-month period, and that aerates it and mixes it at the same time. That's what you're looking to do, and that will reheat the whole pile as it starts to cool down, then it'll use up all the oxygen and cool down, then you mix it again, and the whole thing starts over again. After about three uh good mixes, you'll find that it settles down pretty well after that, and there's not a lot of heat, and that's when it's ready for curing and eventually off to go into the growing space. And this is just fulfilling kind of some of the ideas that I want to take to scale. I think that we use our waste poorly. We need to capture our nitrogen-rich waste because that is what we can use to purify uh our carbon chains that have been become have are totally polluted from the microplastic, the PFAS, from all the different ways that we know that we are toxifying our environment and it's bleeding right through into our agriculture because our organic waste is corrupted with this stuff. And the way to fix that is hot composting, biological breakdown with thermophilic bacteria is the best way to clean that material, and we need to preserve our nitrogen-rich material to do that because that's what the high that's what the hot composting relies on is material rich in nitrogen. You know it's rich in nitrogen when it smells bad still. That's the nitrogen caught in there, but it wants to escape very quickly. Once it's gone, that chance at purifying through hot composting through thermophilic bacteria is gone. So that's what we're capturing here. Anyway, I want to make a quick video. Thanks, y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hi everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 0.32,\n      \"end\": 1.36,\n      \"duration\": 1.04,\n      \"confidence\": 0.977,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" Hi\",\n          \"start\": 0.32,\n          \"end\": 0.64,\n          \"duration\": 0.32,\n          \"confidence\": 0.995\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 0.8,\n          \"end\": 0.96,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 0.96,\n          \"end\": 1.12,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 1.12,\n   